ents and neither substitutes for the other. Where timing is constrained, begin on the recorded side and reserve live visits for confirmed shortlist entries. Live status is reported by the destination platform and can change during any visit, so it is checked there, at the moment it matters. The recorded side also functions as preparation: a clip demonstrates a performer's style directly and at any hour, which makes it the lowest-cost input available for building the live-visit shortlist. Treat the clip as the interview and the live room as the appointment, and the ordering of the visit takes care of itself.</p><h2>Detail Density and Its Uses</h2><p>Listings state unequal amounts about themselves, and the variance is informative rather than defective. A detailed page supports direct comparison; a sparse page delegates its introduction to its clips or its destination. Both are workable inputs — the method simply routes around whichever detail is absent, and no candidate is disqualified for brevity alone.</p><h2>Verification Before Engaging</h2><p>Before any outbound engagement, confirm the performer's name and stated details match the page you intended. Similar stage names occur frequently in this space, and the confirmation habit costs seconds while preventing the standard misdirection. Where conversation matters, weigh what each performer states about their own approach and format before the room, not after.</p><p>Executed in that order — compare, verify access, narrow, confirm — a $cat visit ends with a matched pick, a wide field reduced to one destination, and no surprises left for the platform to deliver.</p>",
